{"title_page": "Betty Meehan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2017}}\n'''Betty Francis Meehan''' (born 1933) is an Australian [[archaeologist]] and [[anthropologist]] who has worked extensively with [[Aboriginal Australians|Aboriginal people]] in [[Arnhem Land]], Northern Territory.\n\n==Early life and education==\nMeehan was born and grew up in [[Bourke, New South Wales]], Australia, in 1933. She was the elder daughter of Francis Owen and Olive Jane Meehan. She attended high school in Bourke and trained as a specialist infants' teacher at [[Bathurst Teachers College]], teaching in [[Bourke, New South Wales|Bourke]], [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], [[Sydney]], and [[Canberra]]. Meehan travelled with her first husband, [[Lester Hiatt]], to the remote [[Northern Territory]] town of [[Maningrida]], in East Arnhem Land, arriving in 1958 on a [[pearling lugger]] to find the Aboriginal community had set up camp on the beach and sent out a [[dugout canoe]] to bring them ashore.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/obituaries/a-culture-made-less-remote/2008/02/20/1203467176647.html Obituaries 'A culture made less remote' 21 February 2008 Les Hiatt, 1931-2008]</ref> There she set up the first school for Aboriginal children at [[Maningrida]], returning in the 1970s to undertake her [[PhD]] fieldwork with her second husband, [[Rhys Jones (archaeologist)|Rhys Jones]].<ref>[https://link.springer.com/referenceworkentry/10.1007%2F978-1-4419-0465-2_2406 Sally Brockwell ''Encyclopedia of Global Archaeology'' 2014, pp 4756-4758 Meehan, Betty]</ref> In 1977, Meehan visited North Arnhem Land to observe the Anbara Aborigines' daily behavior living on the coast.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meehan |first1=Betty |title=Hunters by the seashore |journal=Journal of Human Evolution |date=May 1977 |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=363\u2013370 |doi=10.1016/S0047-2484(77)80005-5}}</ref>\n\nShe studied anthropology at the [[University of Sydney]] from 1962, obtaining an [[Master of Arts|MA]] in anthropology and a PhD at the Department of Prehistory and Anthropology of the [[Australian National University]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bowler |first1=Sandra |last2=Clune |first2=Genevieve |title=That Shadowy Band: The Role of Women in the Development of Australian Archaeology |journal=Australian Archaeology |date=June 2000 |issue=50 |page=32}}</ref>\n\n==Career and recognition==\nMeehan was president of the [[Australian Archaeological Association]] in 1984 and editor of ''[[Australian Archaeology]]'' from 1987-1994.<ref>{{Citation |author1=Meehan, Betty |author2=Jones, Rhys |author3=Australian Archaeological Association |title=Archaeology with ethnography: an Australian perspective |date=1988 |publisher=Dept. of Prehistory, Research School of Pacific Studies, The Australian National University |isbn=978-0-7315-0283-7}}</ref>\n\nShe focused her research on the [[subsistence economy| subsistence regimes]] of an Arnhem Land Aboriginal community<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meehan |first1=Betty |title=Hunters by the Seashore |journal=Journal of Human Evolution |date=1977 |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=363\u2013370|doi=10.1016/S0047-2484(77)80005-5 }}</ref>. She more recently wrote on this region and the confluence of human culture and the environment.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=BOURKE |first1=PATRICIA |last2=BROCKWELLM |first2=SALLY |last3=FAULKNER |first3=PATRICK |last4=MEEHAN |first4=BETTY |title=Climate variability in the mid to late Holocene Arnhem Land Region, North Australia: Archaeological archives of environmental and cultural change |journal=Archaeology in Oceania |date=October 2007 |volume=42 |issue=3 |pages=91\u2013101 |doi=10.1002/j.1834-4453.2007.tb00022.x}}</ref>\n\nShe was made an Honorary Associate of the [[Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology]] at [[Harvard University]] (1995-1996), was director of the [[Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander]] Environment Section of the [[Australian Heritage Commission]] from 1991 to 1995, head of the Aboriginal Section [[National Museum of Australia]] (1990-1991), and a Fellow of the [[Australian Academy of the Humanities]] (1987).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.humanities.org.au/Fellowship/FindFellows/tabid/123/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/1236/Meehan-Betty.aspx |title=Australian Academy of the Humanities Fellows |access-date=27 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527082720/http://www.humanities.org.au/Fellowship/FindFellows/tabid/123/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/1236/Meehan-Betty.aspx |archive-date=27 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHer work is described and lauded in [[Billy Griffiths (writer)|Billy Griffiths]]' 2018 award-winning book ''Deep Time Dreaming: Uncovering Ancient Australia''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Deep Time Dreaming: Uncovering Ancient Australia|date=26 Feb 2018|first=Billy|last=Griffiths|publisher=Black Inc.|isbn=9781760640446}}</ref><ref name=aaadtd>{{cite web | title=Billy Griffiths, Deep Time Dreaming: Uncovering Ancient Australia (Black Inc., 2018) | website=[[Australian Archaeological Association]] | url=https://australianarchaeologicalassociation.com.au/billy-griffiths-deep-time-dreaming-uncovering-ancient-australia-black-inc-2018/ | access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meehan, Betty}}\n[[Category:Australian anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Australian archaeologists]]\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bourke, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Australian National University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women archaeologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2017}}\n'''Betty Francis Meehan''' (born 1933) is an Australian [[archaeologist]] and [[anthropologist]] who has worked extensively with [[Aboriginal Australians|Aboriginal]] tribes in [[Arnhem Land]], Northern Territory.\n==Early life and education==\nMeehan was born and grew up in [[Bourke, New South Wales]], Australia, in 1933. She was the elder daughter of Francis Owen and Olive Jane Meehan. She attended high school in Bourke and trained as a specialist infants' teacher at [[Bathurst Teachers College]], teaching in [[Bourke, New South Wales|Bourke]], [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], [[Sydney]], and [[Canberra]]. Meehan travelled with her first husband, [[Lester Hiatt]], to the remote [[Northern Territory]] town of [[Maningrida]], in East Arnhem Land, arriving in 1958 on a [[pearling lugger]] to find the Aboriginal community had set up camp on the beach and sent out a [[dugout canoe]] to bring them ashore.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/obituaries/a-culture-made-less-remote/2008/02/20/1203467176647.html Obituaries 'A culture made less remote' 21 February 2008 Les Hiatt, 1931-2008]</ref> There she set up the first school for Aboriginal children at [[Maningrida]], returning in the 1970s to undertake her [[PhD]] fieldwork with her second husband, [[Rhys Jones (archaeologist)|Rhys Jones]].<ref>[https://link.springer.com/referenceworkentry/10.1007%2F978-1-4419-0465-2_2406 Sally Brockwell ''Encyclopedia of Global Archaeology'' 2014, pp 4756-4758 Meehan, Betty]</ref> In 1977, Meehan visited North Arnhem Land to observe the Anbara Aborigines' daily behavior living on the coast.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meehan |first1=Betty |title=Hunters by the seashore |journal=Journal of Human Evolution |date=May 1977 |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=363\u2013370 |doi=10.1016/S0047-2484(77)80005-5}}</ref>\n\nShe studied anthropology at the [[University of Sydney]] from 1962, obtaining an [[Master of Arts|MA]] in anthropology and a PhD at the Department of Prehistory and Anthropology of the [[Australian National University]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bowler |first1=Sandra |last2=Clune |first2=Genevieve |title=That Shadowy Band: The Role of Women in the Development of Australian Archaeology |journal=Australian Archaeology |date=June 2000 |issue=50 |page=32}}</ref>\n\n==Career and recognition==\nMeehan was president of the [[Australian Archaeological Association]] in 1984 and editor of ''[[Australian Archaeology]]'' from 1987-1994.<ref>{{Citation |author1=Meehan, Betty |author2=Jones, Rhys |author3=Australian Archaeological Association |title=Archaeology with ethnography: an Australian perspective |date=1988 |publisher=Dept. of Prehistory, Research School of Pacific Studies, The Australian National University |isbn=978-0-7315-0283-7}}</ref>\n\nShe focused her research on the [[subsistence economy| subsistence regimes]] of an Arnhem Land Aboriginal community<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meehan |first1=Betty |title=Hunters by the Seashore |journal=Journal of Human Evolution |date=1977 |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=363\u2013370|doi=10.1016/S0047-2484(77)80005-5 }}</ref>. She more recently wrote on this region and the confluence of human culture and the environment.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=BOURKE |first1=PATRICIA |last2=BROCKWELLM |first2=SALLY |last3=FAULKNER |first3=PATRICK |last4=MEEHAN |first4=BETTY |title=Climate variability in the mid to late Holocene Arnhem Land Region, North Australia: Archaeological archives of environmental and cultural change |journal=Archaeology in Oceania |date=October 2007 |volume=42 |issue=3 |pages=91\u2013101 |doi=10.1002/j.1834-4453.2007.tb00022.x}}</ref>\n\nShe was made an Honorary Associate of the [[Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology]] at [[Harvard University]] (1995-1996), was director of the [[Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander]] Environment Section of the [[Australian Heritage Commission]] from 1991 to 1995, head of the Aboriginal Section [[National Museum of Australia]] (1990-1991), and a Fellow of the [[Australian Academy of the Humanities]] (1987).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.humanities.org.au/Fellowship/FindFellows/tabid/123/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/1236/Meehan-Betty.aspx |title=Australian Academy of the Humanities Fellows |access-date=27 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527082720/http://www.humanities.org.au/Fellowship/FindFellows/tabid/123/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/1236/Meehan-Betty.aspx |archive-date=27 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHer work is described and lauded in [[Billy Griffiths (writer)|Billy Griffiths]]' 2018 award-winning book ''Deep Time Dreaming: Uncovering Ancient Australia''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Deep Time Dreaming: Uncovering Ancient Australia|date=26 Feb 2018|first=Billy|last=Griffiths|publisher=Black Inc.|isbn=9781760640446}}</ref><ref name=aaadtd>{{cite web | title=Billy Griffiths, Deep Time Dreaming: Uncovering Ancient Australia (Black Inc., 2018) | website=[[Australian Archaeological Association]] | url=https://australianarchaeologicalassociation.com.au/billy-griffiths-deep-time-dreaming-uncovering-ancient-australia-black-inc-2018/ | access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meehan, Betty}}\n[[Category:Australian anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Australian archaeologists]]\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bourke, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Australian National University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women archaeologists]]\n", "name_user": "Laterthanyouthink", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Copyedit (minor)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betty_Meehan"}
{"title_page": "Tom Stewart (Scottish footballer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Tom Stewart\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| fullname            = Thomas Stewart\n| birth_date          = \n| birth_place         = [[Lanarkshire]], Scotland\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height              = \n| position            = [[Defender (association football)|Full-back]]\n| youthyears1         = | youthclubs1 = \n| years1              = 1896| clubs1 = [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]| caps1 = | goals1 = \n| years2              = 1896\u20131898| clubs2 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]| caps2 = 27| goals2 = 0\n| years3              = 1898\u20131899| clubs3 = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]| caps3 = 1| goals3 = 0\n}}\n\n'''Thomas '''\"'''Tom'''\"''' Stewart''' was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|full-back]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lamming|first1=Douglas|title=A who's who of Grimsby Town AFC : 1890-1985|date=1985|publisher=Hutton|location=Beverley|isbn=0-907033-34-2|page=100}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Tom}}\n[[Category:People from Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Motherwell F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grimsby Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Tom Stewart\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| fullname            = Thomas Stewart\n| birth_date          = \n| birth_place         = [[Lanarkshire]], Scotland\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height              = \n| position            = [[Defender (association football)|Full-back]]\n| youthyears1         = | youthclubs1 = \n| years1              = 1896| clubs1 = [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]| caps1 = | goals1 = \n| years2              = 1896\u20131898| clubs2 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]| caps2 = 27| goals2 = 0\n| years3              = 1898\u20131899| clubs3 = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]| caps3 = 1| goals3 = 0\n}}\n\n'''Thomas '''\"'''Tom'''\"''' Stewart''' was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|full-back]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lamming|first1=Douglas|title=A who's who of Grimsby Town AFC : 1890-1985|date=1985|publisher=Hutton|location=Beverley|isbn=0-907033-34-2|page=100}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Tom}}\n[[Category:People from Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Motherwell F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grimsby Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Stewart_(Scottish_footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Tom Stanton (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Tom Stanton\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| fullname            = Thomas Stanton\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1948|5|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| height              = \n| position            = [[Defender (association football)|Full back]]/[[Midfielder]]\n| years1              = 1965\u20131966\n| clubs1              = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps1               = 0\n| goals1              = 0\n| years2              = 1966\u20131967\n| clubs2              = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| caps2               = 0\n| goals2              = 0\n| years3              = 1967\u20131968\n| clubs3              = [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]]\n| caps3               = 37\n| goals3              = 1\n| years4              = 1968\u20131976\n| clubs4              = [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]]\n| caps4               = 168\n| goals4              = 7\n| years5              = 1976\u20131977\n| clubs5              = [[Weymouth F.C.|Weymouth]]\n| caps5               = \n| goals5              = \n| years6              = 1977\u20131980\n| clubs6              = [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]]\n| caps6               = \n| goals6              = \n| years7              = 1982\u20131983\n| clubs7              = [[Clevedon Town F.C.|Clevedon Town]]\n| caps7               = \n| goals7              = \n| totalcaps           = 205\n| totalgoals          = 8\n| manageryears1       = 1982\u20131983\n| managerclubs1       = [[Clevedon Town F.C.|Clevedon Town]]\n}}\n'''Thomas Stanton''' (born 3 May 1948 in [[Glasgow]]) is a former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|full back]] and a [[midfielder]] in [[The Football League]] between 1967 and 1976.\n\nStanton started out playing junior football for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] before turning professional in 1965. After a year with their senior squad without playing a League match he moved to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in September 1966, with whom he again failed to play in a League game. He eventually made his League debut after joining [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] in 1967, and went on to play 37 times for them before joining [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] in June 1968.\n\nIn eight seasons with Bristol Rovers he made 168 League appearances, eleven of those as a substitute, and scored seven times, before dropping down into [[non-League football]] in 1976 when he joined [[Weymouth F.C.|Weymouth]]. In 1977, he joined [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]] as a player-[[coach (sport)|coach]], and in 1980 returned to Bristol Rovers as reserve team coach. Another stint as a player-coach followed in 1982, this time with [[Clevedon Town F.C.|Clevedon Town]], and he was later appointed their manager. He returned for a third spell with Bristol Rovers in 1983, where he spent a year coaching their schoolboy teams.\n\nFollowing his retirement from football, Stanton started up an antiques business in the [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]] area of [[Bristol]].\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last1=Byrne |first1=Stephen |last2=Jay |first2=Mike |title=Bristol Rovers Football Club - The Definitive History 1883-2003 |year=2003 |publisher=[[Tempus Publishing|Tempus]] |location=[[Stroud, Gloucestershire|Stroud]] |isbn=0-7524-2717-2 |page=505}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Jay |first1=Mike |last2=Byrne |first2=Stephen |title=Pirates in Profile: A Who's Who of Bristol Rovers Players |year=1994 |publisher=Potten, Baber & Murray |location=[[Bristol]] |isbn=0-9524835-0-5 |page=249}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanton, Tom}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mansfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Weymouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Forest Green Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Clevedon Town F.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Tom Stanton\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| fullname            = Thomas Stanton\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1948|5|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| height              = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}\n| position            = [[Defender (association football)|Full back]]/[[Midfielder]]\n| years1              = 1965\u20131966\n| clubs1              = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps1               = 0\n| goals1              = 0\n| years2              = 1966\u20131967\n| clubs2              = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| caps2               = 0\n| goals2              = 0\n| years3              = 1967\u20131968\n| clubs3              = [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]]\n| caps3               = 37\n| goals3              = 1\n| years4              = 1968\u20131976\n| clubs4              = [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]]\n| caps4               = 168\n| goals4              = 7\n| years5              = 1976\u20131977\n| clubs5              = [[Weymouth F.C.|Weymouth]]\n| caps5               = \n| goals5              = \n| years6              = 1977\u20131980\n| clubs6              = [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]]\n| caps6               = \n| goals6              = \n| years7              = 1982\u20131983\n| clubs7              = [[Clevedon Town F.C.|Clevedon Town]]\n| caps7               = \n| goals7              = \n| totalcaps           = 205\n| totalgoals          = 8\n| manageryears1       = 1982\u20131983\n| managerclubs1       = [[Clevedon Town F.C.|Clevedon Town]]\n}}\n'''Thomas Stanton''' (born 3 May 1948 in [[Glasgow]]) is a former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|full back]] and a [[midfielder]] in [[The Football League]] between 1967 and 1976.\n\nStanton started out playing junior football for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] before turning professional in 1965. After a year with their senior squad without playing a League match he moved to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in September 1966, with whom he again failed to play in a League game. He eventually made his League debut after joining [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] in 1967, and went on to play 37 times for them before joining [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] in June 1968.\n\nIn eight seasons with Bristol Rovers he made 168 League appearances, eleven of those as a substitute, and scored seven times, before dropping down into [[non-League football]] in 1976 when he joined [[Weymouth F.C.|Weymouth]]. In 1977, he joined [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]] as a player-[[coach (sport)|coach]], and in 1980 returned to Bristol Rovers as reserve team coach. Another stint as a player-coach followed in 1982, this time with [[Clevedon Town F.C.|Clevedon Town]], and he was later appointed their manager. He returned for a third spell with Bristol Rovers in 1983, where he spent a year coaching their schoolboy teams.\n\nFollowing his retirement from football, Stanton started up an antiques business in the [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]] area of [[Bristol]].\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last1=Byrne |first1=Stephen |last2=Jay |first2=Mike |title=Bristol Rovers Football Club - The Definitive History 1883-2003 |year=2003 |publisher=[[Tempus Publishing|Tempus]] |location=[[Stroud, Gloucestershire|Stroud]] |isbn=0-7524-2717-2 |page=505}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Jay |first1=Mike |last2=Byrne |first2=Stephen |title=Pirates in Profile: A Who's Who of Bristol Rovers Players |year=1994 |publisher=Potten, Baber & Murray |location=[[Bristol]] |isbn=0-9524835-0-5 |page=249}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanton, Tom}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mansfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Weymouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Forest Green Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Clevedon Town F.C. players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, remove unref height", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Stanton_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Ella baila sola", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Ella baila sola\n|image             = \n|caption        = \n|image_size        = \n|background      = group_or_band\n|origin          = [[Madrid]], [[Spain]]\n|genre           = [[pop music|Pop]]\n|years_active    = [[1996 in music|1996]]\u2014[[2001 in music|2001]]; [[2009 in music|2009]]\u2014[[2013 in music|2013]]; [[2015 in music|2015]]\u2014present\n|label           = [[EMI]]-Odeon\n|associated_acts = \n|website             = [http://ellabailasola.yaia.com/ fansite]\n|current_members = {{plainlist|\n*[[Marta Bot\u00eda Alonso|Marta Bot\u00eda]]\n*Virginia Mos}}\n|past_members    = {{plainlist|\n*[[Marilia Andr\u00e9s Casares|Marilia Andr\u00e9s]] {{small|(1996-2001)}}\n*Roc\u00edo Pav\u00f3n {{small|(2009-2013)}}\n*Mar\u00eda del Mar Garc\u00eda {{small|(2015-2018)}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Ella baila sola''' ({{lang-en|She dances alone}}) is a [[Spain|Spanish]] musical duet formed by [[Marta Bot\u00eda Alonso]] ([[Madrid]], Spain, September 15, 1974) and [[Marilia Andr\u00e9s Casares]] ([[Cuenca, Spain|Cuenca]], Spain,  December 17, 1974). The group dissolved in 2001. The group is active right now touring Latin America with Marta, Marilia is not in the band anymore.\n\n== History ==\n[[Marilia Andr\u00e9s Casares]] and [[Marta Bot\u00eda]] met while studying at Madrid\u2019s [[San Agustin School]].<ref name=\"mn0000177817\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ella-baila-sola-mn0000177817/biography |title=Artist Biography by Drago Bonacich |publisher=All Music}}</ref> Originally, the duo were dubbed \u2018The Just\u2019,<ref name=\"mn0000177817\"/> and sang exclusively in English. However, once producer [[Gonzalo Benavides]]<ref name=\"mn0000177817\"/> listened to a demo by the duo, he convinced them to begin singing in Spanish. Upon switching languages, the group also underwent a transformation of its own. The duo, now titled \u2018Ella Baila Sola\u2019 (inspired by the song \u2018They Dance Alone\u2019 by [[Sting (musician)|Sting]]<ref name=\"spainsnews.com\">{{cite web |url=https://spainsnews.com/what-have-marta-and-marilia-done-before-the-return-of-ella-baila-sola/ |title=What have Marta and Marilia done before the return of 'Ella baila sola'? |publisher=Spains News}}</ref>) recorded its first self titled album in 1996. Their musical style consisted of a mix of [[Latin Cantautor]], [[Latin Pop]], [[Spanish Pop]] and [[Spanish Pop Rock]].<ref name=\"wegow.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wegow.com/en-us/artists/ella-baila-sola}}</ref> Just a year later, the group was awarded the \u2018Best Spanish Band\u2019 award at \u2018[[Premios Amigos]]\u2019. The group\u2019s debut album was a huge hit in [[Spain]], selling over a million copies. The album also generally sold very well across [[Latin America]]. Songs such as \u2018Lo echamos a suertes\u2019 and \u2018Amores de barra\u2019 quickly became staple hits of the 1990s in Spain.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spainculture.us/city/washington-dc/ella-baila-sola-amistades-peligrosas-in-washington-dc/ |title=Ella Baila Sola & Amistades Peligrosas in Washington, D.C. |date=22 March 2017}}</ref> To this date, the duo has toured places such as [[Mexico]], [[Chile]], [[America]] and [[Madrid]].<ref name=\"wegow.com\"/> In the last months before the separation of \u2018Ella Baila Sola\u2019, the distance between the duo became increasingly evident as they avoided each other completely. Furthermore, After her departure from \u2018Ella Baila Sola\u2019 Marilia Andr\u00e9s Casares continued to pursue her individual artistic passions and continued her career as a singer songwriter<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.telemadrid.es/programas/buenos-dias-madrid-om/Marilia-etapa-cambio-9-2197070286--20200120034055.html |title=Marilia: \"Estoy en una etapa de cambio\" }}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n\nShortly after their first album in 1996, The duo released two more albums which furthered their success and notoriety in the Latin world. However, due to personal differences, in 2001, Marta and Marilia chose to part ways<ref name=\"spainsnews.com\"/><ref name=\"discogs.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1051531-Ella-Baila-Sola?recent=true}}</ref> and pursue their own musical careers and lifestyles. Recently, after years of inactivity, Marta Bot\u00eda relaunched the group with new member [[Roc\u00edo Pav\u00f3n]]. With Pav\u00f3n, \u2018Ella Baila Sola\u2019 released two new albums in 2009-2010 dubbed [[\u2018Awake\u2019]] and [[\u2018Grandes Exitos\u2019]]. \u2018Awake\u2019<ref name=\"spainsnews.com\"/> consisted of new music and a new tour across Spain, whilst \u2018Grandes Exitos\u2019 was a [[compilation album|compilation]]<ref name=\"discogs.com\"/> of the duo\u2019s greatest hits from the 90\u2019s. In 2013 the band was dissolved and Roc\u00edo Pav\u00f3n left the group after a collection of reproaches over [[Facebook]]. Soon after Pav\u00f3n\u2019s departure, in 2015,<ref name=\"spainsnews.com\"/> Marta brought in [[Mar\u00eda del Mar Garc\u00eda]] (2015-2018) to accompany her on tours. Later, the group relaunched for a fourth time in 2018 with another new member, [[Virginia Mos]] and have recently hinted at new music.\n\n== Discography ==\n* ''[[Ella baila sola (album)|Ella baila sola]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[E.B.S. (album)|E.B.S.]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Marta y Marilia]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Grandes \u00e9xitos (Ella baila sola)|Grandes \u00e9xitos]]'' (2001)\n\n===Collaborations===\n* ''[[Mira que eres canalla Aute]]'' (Ella baila sola - Ay de ti, Ay de m\u00ed)\n* ''[[Mujer (2001 album)|Mujer]]'' (Ella baila sola - No sabes como sufr\u00ed || Todos - Hay que volver a empezar)\n* ''[[Homenaje a Jes\u00fas de la Rosa]]'' (Marilia - Tu frialdad || Todos - Recuerdos de una noche)\n* ''[[Elefantes (band)|Elefantes]]'' (Elefantes & Marilia - Me gustar\u00eda hacerte feliz)\n* ''[[Se vende]]'' (Tonxu & Marta Bot\u00eda - Risk || Tonxu & Ella baila sola - El caprichoso)\n* ''[[Vampiros en La Habana]]'' (Guaran\u00e1 & Marta Bot\u00eda - \u00c9chame a m\u00ed la culpa)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* {{cite web |last1=Bonacich |first1=Drago |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ella-baila-sola-mn0000177817/biography |title=Artist Biography by Drago Bonacich |website=All Music |accessdate=3 February 2020}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.spainculture.us/city/washington-dc/ella-baila-sola-amistades-peligrosas-in-washington-dc/ |title=Ella Baila Sola & Amistades Peligrosas in Washington, D.C. |date=22 March 2017 |website=Spain Culture |accessdate=3 February 2020}}\n* {{cite web |title=Ella Baila Sola |url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1051531-Ella-Baila-Sola?recent=true |website=Discogs}}\n* {{cite web |title=Ella Baila Sola Instagram |url=https://www.instagram.com/ellabailasolaoficial/?hl=en |website=Instagram}}\n* {{cite web |title=Ella Baila Sola |url=https://www.wegow.com/en-us/artists/ella-baila-sola |website=Wegow}}\n* {{cite web |title=What have Marta and Marilia done before the return of 'Ella Baila Sola' |url=https://spainsnews.com/what-have-marta-and-marilia-done-before-the-return-of-ella-baila-sola/ |website=Spain's News |accessdate=3 February 2020}}\n* {{cite web |title=Marilia: \"Estoy en una etapa de cambio\" |url=http://www.telemadrid.es/programas/buenos-dias-madrid-om/Marilia-etapa-cambio-9-2197070286--20200120034055.html |website=Telemadrid.es |publisher=Telemadrid}}\n* {{cite web |title=Marta Bot\u00eda, cero relaci\u00f3n con Marilia y nueva vida con 'Ella baila sola' con Virginia Mos |url=https://www.europapress.es/chance/cineymusica/noticia-marta-botia-cero-relacion-marilia-nueva-vida-ella-baila-sola-virginia-mos-20181211103144.html |website=EuroPapress |publisher=EuroPapress |accessdate=3 February 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Spanish pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2001]]\n[[Category:Latin pop music groups]]\n\n\n{{Spain-band-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Ella baila sola\n|image             = \n|caption        = \n|image_size        = \n|background      = group_or_band\n|origin          = [[Madrid]], [[Spain]]\n|genre           = [[pop music|Pop]]\n|years_active    = [[1996 in music|1996]]\u2014[[2001 in music|2001]]; [[2009 in music|2009]]\u2014[[2013 in music|2013]]; [[2015 in music|2015]]\u2014present\n|label           = [[EMI]]-Odeon\n|associated_acts = \n|website             = [http://ellabailasola.yaia.com/ fansite]\n|current_members = {{plainlist|\n*[[Marta Bot\u00eda Alonso|Marta Bot\u00eda]]\n*Virginia Mos}}\n|past_members    = {{plainlist|\n*[[Marilia Andr\u00e9s Casares|Marilia Andr\u00e9s]] {{small|(1996-2001)}}\n*Roc\u00edo Pav\u00f3n {{small|(2009-2013)}}\n*Mar\u00eda del Mar Garc\u00eda {{small|(2015-2018)}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Ella baila sola''' ({{lang-en|She dances alone}}) is a [[Spain|Spanish]] musical duet formed by [[Marta Bot\u00eda Alonso]] ([[Madrid]], Spain, September 15, 1974) and [[Marilia Andr\u00e9s Casares]] ([[Cuenca, Spain|Cuenca]], Spain,  December 17, 1974). The group dissolved in 2001. The group is active right now touring Latin America with Marta, Marilia is not in the band anymore.\n\n== History ==\n[[Marilia Andr\u00e9s Casares]] and [[Marta Bot\u00eda]] met while studying at Madrid\u2019s [[San Agustin School]].<ref name=\"mn0000177817\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ella-baila-sola-mn0000177817/biography |title=Artist Biography by Drago Bonacich |publisher=All Music}}</ref> Originally, the duo were dubbed \u2018The Just\u2019,<ref name=\"mn0000177817\"/> and sang exclusively in English. However, once producer [[Gonzalo Benavides]]<ref name=\"mn0000177817\"/> listened to a demo by the duo, he convinced them to begin singing in Spanish. Upon switching languages, the group also underwent a transformation of its own. The duo, now titled \u2018Ella Baila Sola\u2019 (inspired by the song \u2018They Dance Alone\u2019 by [[Sting (musician)|Sting]]<ref name=\"spainsnews.com\">{{cite web |url=https://spainsnews.com/what-have-marta-and-marilia-done-before-the-return-of-ella-baila-sola/ |title=What have Marta and Marilia done before the return of 'Ella baila sola'? |publisher=Spains News}}</ref>) recorded its first self titled album in 1996. Their musical style consisted of a mix of [[Latin Cantautor]], [[Latin Pop]], [[Spanish Pop]] and [[Spanish Pop Rock]].<ref name=\"wegow.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wegow.com/en-us/artists/ella-baila-sola}}</ref> Just a year later, the group was awarded the \u2018Best Spanish Band\u2019 award at \u2018[[Premios Amigos]]\u2019. The group\u2019s debut album was a huge hit in [[Spain]], selling over a million copies. The album also generally sold very well across [[Latin America]]. Songs such as \u2018Lo echamos a suertes\u2019 and \u2018Amores de barra\u2019 quickly became staple hits of the 1990s in Spain.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spainculture.us/city/washington-dc/ella-baila-sola-amistades-peligrosas-in-washington-dc/ |title=Ella Baila Sola & Amistades Peligrosas in Washington, D.C. |date=22 March 2017}}</ref> To this date, the duo has toured places such as [[Mexico]], [[Chile]], [[America]] and [[Madrid]].<ref name=\"wegow.com\"/> In the last months before the separation of \u2018Ella Baila Sola\u2019, the distance between the duo became increasingly evident as they avoided each other completely. Furthermore, After her departure from \u2018Ella Baila Sola\u2019 Marilia Andr\u00e9s Casares continued to pursue her individual artistic passions and continued her career as a singer songwriter<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.telemadrid.es/programas/buenos-dias-madrid-om/Marilia-etapa-cambio-9-2197070286--20200120034055.html |title=Marilia: \"Estoy en una etapa de cambio\" }}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n\nShortly after their first album in 1996, The duo released two more albums which furthered their success and notoriety in the Latin world. However, due to personal differences, in 2001, Marta and Marilia chose to part ways<ref name=\"spainsnews.com\"/><ref name=\"discogs.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1051531-Ella-Baila-Sola?recent=true}}</ref> and pursue their own musical careers and lifestyles. Recently, after years of inactivity, Marta Bot\u00eda relaunched the group with new member [[Roc\u00edo Pav\u00f3n]]. With Pav\u00f3n, \u2018Ella Baila Sola\u2019 released two new albums in 2009-2010 dubbed [[\u2018Awake\u2019]] and [[\u2018Grandes Exitos\u2019]]. \u2018Awake\u2019<ref name=\"spainsnews.com\"/> consisted of new music and a new tour across Spain, whilst \u2018Grandes Exitos\u2019 was a [[Compilation|compilation]]<ref name=\"discogs.com\"/> of the duo\u2019s greatest hits from the 90\u2019s. In 2013 the band was dissolved and Roc\u00edo Pav\u00f3n left the group after a collection of reproaches over [[Facebook]]. Soon after Pav\u00f3n\u2019s departure, in 2015,<ref name=\"spainsnews.com\"/> Marta brought in [[Mar\u00eda del Mar Garc\u00eda]] (2015-2018) to accompany her on tours. Later, the group relaunched for a fourth time in 2018 with another new member, [[Virginia Mos]] and have recently hinted at new music.\n\n== Discography ==\n* ''[[Ella baila sola (album)|Ella baila sola]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[E.B.S. (album)|E.B.S.]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Marta y Marilia]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Grandes \u00e9xitos (Ella baila sola)|Grandes \u00e9xitos]]'' (2001)\n\n===Collaborations===\n* ''[[Mira que eres canalla Aute]]'' (Ella baila sola - Ay de ti, Ay de m\u00ed)\n* ''[[Mujer (2001 album)|Mujer]]'' (Ella baila sola - No sabes como sufr\u00ed || Todos - Hay que volver a empezar)\n* ''[[Homenaje a Jes\u00fas de la Rosa]]'' (Marilia - Tu frialdad || Todos - Recuerdos de una noche)\n* ''[[Elefantes (band)|Elefantes]]'' (Elefantes & Marilia - Me gustar\u00eda hacerte feliz)\n* ''[[Se vende]]'' (Tonxu & Marta Bot\u00eda - Risk || Tonxu & Ella baila sola - El caprichoso)\n* ''[[Vampiros en La Habana]]'' (Guaran\u00e1 & Marta Bot\u00eda - \u00c9chame a m\u00ed la culpa)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* {{cite web |last1=Bonacich |first1=Drago |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ella-baila-sola-mn0000177817/biography |title=Artist Biography by Drago Bonacich |website=All Music |accessdate=3 February 2020}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.spainculture.us/city/washington-dc/ella-baila-sola-amistades-peligrosas-in-washington-dc/ |title=Ella Baila Sola & Amistades Peligrosas in Washington, D.C. |date=22 March 2017 |website=Spain Culture |accessdate=3 February 2020}}\n* {{cite web |title=Ella Baila Sola |url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1051531-Ella-Baila-Sola?recent=true |website=Discogs}}\n* {{cite web |title=Ella Baila Sola Instagram |url=https://www.instagram.com/ellabailasolaoficial/?hl=en |website=Instagram}}\n* {{cite web |title=Ella Baila Sola |url=https://www.wegow.com/en-us/artists/ella-baila-sola |website=Wegow}}\n* {{cite web |title=What have Marta and Marilia done before the return of 'Ella Baila Sola' |url=https://spainsnews.com/what-have-marta-and-marilia-done-before-the-return-of-ella-baila-sola/ |website=Spain's News |accessdate=3 February 2020}}\n* {{cite web |title=Marilia: \"Estoy en una etapa de cambio\" |url=http://www.telemadrid.es/programas/buenos-dias-madrid-om/Marilia-etapa-cambio-9-2197070286--20200120034055.html |website=Telemadrid.es |publisher=Telemadrid}}\n* {{cite web |title=Marta Bot\u00eda, cero relaci\u00f3n con Marilia y nueva vida con 'Ella baila sola' con Virginia Mos |url=https://www.europapress.es/chance/cineymusica/noticia-marta-botia-cero-relacion-marilia-nueva-vida-ella-baila-sola-virginia-mos-20181211103144.html |website=EuroPapress |publisher=EuroPapress |accessdate=3 February 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Spanish pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2001]]\n[[Category:Latin pop music groups]]\n\n\n{{Spain-band-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Compilation\u2192compilation album", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ella_baila_sola"}
{"title_page": "Mission Hill (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|American animated television series}}\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2010}}\n{{Infobox television\n| image        = Mission Hill.png\n| caption      = The heads of the five main characters. Counter clockwise from bottom left-hand corner: Andy French, Posey Tyler, Kevin French, and Jim Kuback, with Stogie <small>(the dog)</small> in the middle.\n| show_name_2  = The Downtowners <small>(original title)</small>\n| genre        = [[Sitcom]]<br />[[Comedy-drama|Dramedy]]\n| creator      = [[Bill Oakley]]<br />[[Josh Weinstein]]\n| starring     = [[Wallace Langham]]<br />[[Scott Menville]]<br />[[Brian Posehn]]<br />[[Vicki Lewis]]<br />[[Nick Jameson]]<br />[[Tom Kenny]]\n| opentheme    = \"[[Italian Leather Sofa]]\" by [[Cake (band)|Cake]]\n| composer     = Eric Speier\n| executive_producer = Bill Oakley<br />Josh Weinstein\n| producer     = Colin A.B.V. Lewis\n| country      = United States\n| num_seasons  = 1\n| num_episodes = 13\n| list_episodes = #Episodes\n| runtime      = 21\u201323 minutes\n| company      = The Tannebaum Company<br />[[Bill Oakley]]/[[Josh Weinstein|Josh Weinstein Productions]]<br />[[Castle Rock Entertainment]]\n| distributor  = [[Warner Bros. Television]]\n| network      = [[The WB]] {{small|(1999\u20132000)}}<br />[[Adult Swim]] {{small|(2002)}}\n| picture_format = [[4:3]] [[standard-definition television|SDTV]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|1999|9|24}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2002|8|11}}\n}}\n'''''Mission Hill''''' (originally titled '''''The Downtowners''''')<ref>{{cite web|title=Warner Renames The Downtowners|url=http://www.awn.com/mag/issue4.06/4.06pages/news/television.php3|date=September 1999|work=Animation World Magazine|issue=4.6|publisher=[[Animation World Network]]|accessdate=1 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402155123/http://www.awn.com/mag/issue4.06/4.06pages/news/television.php3|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=dead}}</ref> is an American [[animated television series]] that ran on [[The WB]] from September 24, 1999, to July 16, 2000, and on [[Adult Swim]] from July 14 to August 11, 2002.<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=399-400}}</ref> Although 18 episodes were planned, only 13 were produced. The series was put on hiatus by the WB Network after two episodes due to poor ratings. It returned to the WB in the summer of 2000 but was canceled after four additional episodes. The series went on to develop a [[cult following]], thanks to repeated airings of all 13 episodes on [[Teletoon]]'s Teletoon Unleashed block; [[Cartoon Network]]'s popular late night programming block [[Adult Swim]]; and Too Funny To Sleep, a late night programming block on [[TBS (TV Network)|TBS]]. ''Mission Hill'' was formerly known as ''The Downtowners'', although [[MTV]]'s production of the similarly titled ''[[Downtown (TV series)|Downtown]]'' forced a name change.\n\nIt has also been popular outside of the United States and Canada, receiving broadcasts in Australia, [[Eastern Europe]], [[Latin America]], Spain and [[New Zealand]].\nStylistically, the series is recognizable for its bright, [[neon]] color palette, and features a peculiar mixture of modern animation and traditional \"cartoonish\" drawings (dashed lines coming from eyes to indicate line of vision, red bolts of lightning around a spot in pain). The style was made to be reminiscent of Warner Bros. cartoons from the 1930s to 1950s, as well as 1960's [[Hanna-Barbera]] cartoons. The designs were done by [[Lauren MacMullan]], who cites the comic series ''[[Eightball (comics)|Eightball]]'' as her source of inspiration for her overall design.\n\nThe series was created in 1997<ref>https://www.polygon.com/2017/9/6/16256458/mission-hill-simpsons-bill-oakley-josh-weinstein-matt-groening</ref> by [[Bill Oakley]] and [[Josh Weinstein]], former executive producers of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', and the artistic designer was [[Lauren MacMullan]]. It features the [[voice actor|voices]] of [[Wallace Langham]], [[Scott Menville]], [[Brian Posehn]], [[Vicki Lewis]], [[Nick Jameson]], [[Tom Kenny]], [[Herbert Siguenza]], [[Jane Wiedlin]], [[Tress MacNeille]] and [[Lisa Arch|Lisa Kushell]]. The [[theme music|theme song]] is a faster, instrumental version of \"Italian Leather Sofa\" by [[Cake (band)|Cake]].\n\n[[Warner Home Video]] released all 13 completed episodes on [[DVD]], on November 29, 2005.\n\n==Premise==\nSet in the world of teens and 20-somethings, this series follows hip 24-year-old Andy French, whose sheltered suburban teenage brother Kevin moves in with him and his roommates in a big-city loft.\n\n==Characters==\n\n===Main===\n* Andrew \"Andy\" French ([[Wallace Langham]]) \u2013 A 24-year-old in his third consecutive \"post-college slump year.\" Andy is an aspiring cartoonist. From the pilot episode to \"Unemployment, Part 1,\" Andy worked at a waterbed store where his boss was a lecherous, short, ill-tempered, foul-mouthed man who frequented strip clubs. From \"Unemployment, Part 2\" to \"Plan 9 from Mission Hill\" (and including the unproduced episodes \"Supertool\" and \"Pretty in Pink\"), Andy works as an artist at the same advertising agency as Jim. Often bored and mellow, Andy is easily annoyed by his younger brother, Kevin, though it has been shown that Andy does indeed care about him. However, he often has a habit of calling him and others \"douchebag\".\n* Kevin French ([[Scott Menville]]) \u2013 Andy's 17-year-old nerd brother. Kevin moved in with Andy when his parents left for [[Wyoming]], bringing his sheltered, suburban mindset to Mission Hill.  He hopes to attend [[Yale University]], and prides himself on his SAT scores.  He has a habit of \"bling-blonging,\" saying \"bling blong\" over and over again while doing homework to drown out any/all distractions and is prone to heavily overreact to trivial matters.\n* James \"Jim\" Kuback ([[Brian Posehn]]) \u2013 In his mid-20s, loftmate Jim has been Andy's best friend since high school. He is extremely tall and lanky, with red hair and a beard much like his voice actor, and speaks in a deep, monotone voice. Jim is a genius at all things electronic, whether it's electronic music or computers. He is mellow and able to express a wide variety of sentiments by nuancing the word \"Okay.\" Jim is a high-powered advertising agent who is paid vast amounts of money to alter marketing campaigns to appeal to [[Millennial Generation|Generation Y]].\n* Posey Tyler ([[Vicki Lewis]]) \u2013 In her mid 20s, Posey, the fourth hippie loftmate, is somewhat a flower child, and very concerned about the health and well-being of her plants. She often gives her vegetables to charity, but gets upset when they are damaged. She often speaks quickly and in a nervous tone.\n* Stogie \u2013 Andy's pet [[Golden Retriever]], who can apparently stomach anything from alcohol drinks to remote controls. At one point in the series his primary source of food was eating the couch cushions. Posey has stated that \"there are dark forces at work within him\", in the first episode.\n\n===Supporting===\n* Gus Duncz ([[Nick Jameson]]) \u2013 A [[homosexual|gay]] man in his late 60s, he owns a diner in Mission Hill. He is a very large, burly man with a short temper and is married to Wally.  According to [[audio commentary]] by the producers, Gus is based on [[Broderick Crawford]], though according to the audio commentary for ''[[The Simpsons]]'' seventh season episode, \"[[Marge Be Not Proud]],\" Bill Oakley and Josh Weinstein claim the inspiration for the character was [[Lawrence Tierney]] (who voiced the Try-N-Save store detective who catches Bart shoplifting).\n* Wally Langford ([[Tom Kenny]]) \u2013 A gay man in his late 60s, Wally is a [[movie projector|projectionist]] at the local [[art film|art movie]] house.  He is based on [[David Niven]]. He enjoys cinema and ragtime music. In the episode \"I Married a Gay Man from Outer Space\", it is revealed that he directed a film in the 1950s entitled ''The Man from Pluto'' (which parodied ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]''). It starred his partner Gus in the title role.\n* Natalie Leibowitz-Hernandez ([[Vicki Lewis]]) \u2013 Late 20s. Politically correct and intellectually well-endowed, Natalie is a professor of Women's Studies at the local college. Sensitive to biases in our culture, Natalie and her husband have yet to name their baby as they want it to have cultural significance reflective of their own respective cultures. She is of Jewish religion. She is a working mother who supports both \"Baby Nameless\" and her non-working \"marital partner\" Carlos. The character of Natalie was based and modeled on the writer and educator [[Lois M. Leveen]], a longtime friend of the show's creators. She auditioned for the voice of her own character, but the actress Vicki Lewis was determined to be even more \"Lois-y\" than Lois Leveen herself, and she was cast in the role instead.<ref>https://twitter.com/thatbilloakley/status/2150587298750464 {{dead link|date=December 2017|url=|bot=TweetCiteBot}}</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/thatbilloakley/status/2150853913870336 {{dead link|date=December 2017|url=|bot=TweetCiteBot}}</ref>\n* Carlos Hernandez ([[Herbert Siguenza]]) \u2013 Late 20s. He is a struggling Latino artist and [[stay-at-home dad]] for Baby Nameless. Unlike his wife Natalie, Carlos is a [[Christians|Christian]], his work is, at times, reminiscent of [[Jackson Pollock]], [[Diego Rivera]] and [[Bob Ross]]. He prides himself on having no discernible style. Carlos and Natalie have a pet snake as a result of an episode involving a raid on an animal testing lab.\n* Gwen ([[Jane Wiedlin]]) \u2013 Early 20s. Andy's on-and-off girlfriend, Gwen completed two years of community college before settling in Mission Hill. She met Andy working at Ron's [[Waterbed]] World. Someday she'd like to be an accomplished person who achieves her goals and makes a serious contribution to society. She likes [[The Go-Go's]].\n* Toby Mundorf ([[Josh Weinstein]]) \u2013 In his late teens and one of Kevin's best friends in Mission Hill. His overprotective mother worries a great deal about him, as he frequently suffers from allergies, asthma, and hunger. Despite his large size, he is a born coward.\n*  George Bang ([[Bill Oakley]]) \u2013 Kevin's other best friend. George works long hours after school in his father's market. George is extremely competitive in everything from taking tests to playing [[video game]]s. He shares all the same interests as his best friends and is particularly proud of owning the complete [[Babylon 5 Collectible Card Game]]. Unlike his friends Toby and Kevin, his parents don't seem to be overprotective, so he is more sarcastic and aggressive than either of them. George has an older sister named Tina who goes to Polytech. George is of Korean descent.\n* Ron ([[Nick Jameson]]) \u2013 A sleazy, immoral Armenian (though the commentary described Ron as being from a country that used to be a part of the [[Soviet Union]], which does include Armenia, but could also be any number of countries from Eastern Europe and Central Asia) man and former boss of Andy (who loathes him). On \"Unemployment, Part 1,\" Ron was arrested for tax evasion and his store was confiscated by the government. He has an extremely short temper and often takes his rage out on his employees.\n\n==Production==\n{{empty section|date=March 2018}}\n\n==Episodes==\nThirteen episodes of the series were produced while five more were written, but never completed. [[Traditional animation#Animatic|Animatics]] for some of these episodes were in production at the time of the series' cancellation. It was planned to put these animatics on the DVD for the series, but this never came to fruition. However, several of the animatics\u2014including a completed video animatic and synchronized audio read-through of the episode \"Pretty in Pink (Crap Gets in Your Eyes)\"\u2014have been released through various internet outlets.\n\n===Only-series (1999\u20132002)===\n{{Episode table\n|background=#7ea6e2\n|overall=\n|title=25\n|director=\n|writer=\n|airdate=\n|prodcode=\n|country=US\n|episodes=\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber = 1\n|Title = Pilot (or The Douchebag Aspect)\n|DirectedBy = [[Lauren MacMullan]]\n|WrittenBy = [[Bill Oakley]] & [[Josh Weinstein]]\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1999|9|24}}\n|ProdCode = 3950-01\n|ShortSummary = Andy French, an aspiring cartoonist working at a waterbed store run by a sleazy, ambiguously Eastern European man named Ron, is forced to take in his annoying little brother, Kevin, after Andy's parents decide to move away to Wyoming and not take Kevin with them.\n''Music'': \"Burning Flies\" by [[Looper (band)|Looper]], \"Couldn't You Wait\" (Acoustic Version) by [[Silkworm (band)|Silkworm]], \"Don't Let the Bastards Grind You Down\" by [[The Toasters]], \"Rude Boy Rock\" by [[Lionrock]]\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber = 2\n|Title = Andy Joins the PTA (or Great Sexpectations)\n|DirectedBy = Gary McCarver\n|WrittenBy = [[Andrew Kreisberg]]\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2002|5|26}} <small>(on [[Adult Swim]])</small>\n|ProdCode = 3950-02\n|ShortSummary = When Andy attends Kevin's parent-teacher conference en lieu of their mother and father, he joins the PTA in order to impress Kevin's English teacher. Meanwhile, Kevin becomes obsessed with an online role playing game.<br />''Music'': \"Machete\" by [[Moby]], \"Do That Thing\" by [[The Halo Benders]], \"[[Major Leagues (EP)|Major Leagues]]\" by [[Pavement (band)|Pavement]]\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber = 3\n|Title = Kevin's Problem (or Porno for Pyro)\n|DirectedBy = Tricia Garcia\n|WrittenBy = J. David Stem & [[David N. Weiss]]\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1999|10|8}}\n|ProdCode =3950-03\n|ShortSummary =Kevin faces a moral dilemma when two bullies (Griffo and C-Dog) get blamed for burning down the Mission Hill market, which was an accident Kevin caused after trying to hide a [[pornographic]] magazine after one of the bullies catches him [[masturbating]] to it. Meanwhile, Jim returns from Japan wearing Day-Glo short-shorts which becomes popular with everyone (except Andy).\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber = 4\n|Title = Andy Vs. The Real World (or The Big-Ass Viacom Lawsuit)\n|DirectedBy = Christian Roman\n|WrittenBy = Ben Kull\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|6|9}}\n|ProdCode =3950-04\n|ShortSummary =Kevin finds a collection of old videos chronicling the time that MTV's ''[[The Real World]]'' filmed a season in Mission Hill\u2014and how Andy became part of the cast after one of the house mates gets hit by a bus.<br />''Music'': \"Ape Self Prevails in Me Still\" by [[Quasi]], \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" by [[R.E.M.]], \"Begin\" by [[Lambchop (band)|Lambchop]], \"Bad Boys\" by [[Inner Circle (band)|Inner Circle]] \"Who's Afraid of Elizabeth Taylor\" by [[Joan of Arc (band)|Joan of Arc]]\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber = 5\n|Title = Andy and Kevin Make a Friend (or One Bang for Two Brothers)\n|DirectedBy = [[Mike Kim]]\n|WrittenBy = [[Michael Panes]]\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|6|25}}\n|ProdCode =3950-05\n|ShortSummary =Kevin and Andy fight for the affections of George's sister. Meanwhile, Gus gets stabbed in the head and Wally urges him to go to the hospital to have the knife removed.  <br />''Music'': \"Ape Self Prevails in Me Still\" by [[Quasi]], \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" by [[R.E.M.]], \"Begin\" by [[Lambchop (band)|Lambchop]], \"Who's Afraid of Elizabeth Taylor\" by [[Joan of Arc (band)|Joan of Arc]], \"Sideshow\" by [[The Wake (US band)|The Wake]], \"Dying Culture\" by [[Wumpscut]]\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber = 6\n|Title = Andy Gets a Promotion (or How to Get Head in Business Without Really Trying)\n|DirectedBy = [[Dominic Polcino]]\n|WrittenBy = Michael Panes\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|7|9}}\n|ProdCode =3950-06\n|ShortSummary =After having his work rejected by nearly every magazine, Andy decides to abandon his dreams as a cartoonist and become Ron's assistant at the waterbed store, which changes Andy's personality for the worse.<br />''Music'': \"[[Blue Monday (New Order song)|Blue Monday]]\" by [[New Order (band)|New Order]], \"[[Do You Really Want to Hurt Me]]\" by [[Culture Club]], \"[[Le Freak]]\" by [[Chic (band)|Chic]]\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber = 7\n|Title = Kevin Vs. the SAT (or Nocturnal Admissions)\n|DirectedBy = Ilya Skorupsky\n|WrittenBy = J. David Stem & David N. Weiss\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|7|2}}\n|ProdCode =3950-07\n|ShortSummary =Kevin and his friends work furiously to crack the code for perfect scores on the SATs after learning that Ivy League schools aren't accepting students unless they have perfect SAT scores (800 Math, 800 Verbal) or are involved in extracurricular activities. Meanwhile, Posey advertises her massage services in a newspaper\u2014which lands her in trouble with a local pimp.\n| LineColor = 7ea6e2\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber = 8\n|Title =Unemployment Part 1 (or Brother's Big Boner)\n|DirectedBy = Scott Alberts\n|WrittenBy = Robin Stein\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|7|16}}\n|ProdCode =3950-08\n|ShortSummary =Andy, who just blew his parents' $400 living allowance on an organ in a desperate attempt to have fun without getting drunk or having sex, finds himself unemployed when Ron gets arrested for tax evasion and the waterbed store is seized by the government. When Andy can't hold down a job, Kevin goes to Ron to sign a form that activates Andy's unemployment payment\u2014and becomes the owner of Ron's Ferraro.<br />''Music'': \"[[Sundown (Gordon Lightfoot song)|Sundown]]\" by [[Gordon Lightfoot]], \"[[In-A-Gadda-Da-Vida]]